The Arrow or Hetz (, ) is a family of anti-ballistic missiles designed to fulfill an Israeli requirement for a theater missile defense system that would be more effective against ballistic missiles than the MIM-104 Patriot surface-to-air missile. Jointly funded and produced by Israel and the United States, development of the system began in 1986 and has continued since,1 drawing some contested criticism.2 Undertaken by Israel Aerospace Industries (IAI) and Boeing, it is overseen by the Israeli Ministry of Defence's &quot;Homa&quot; (, , &quot;rampart&quot;) missile defense agency and the U.S. Missile Defense Agency.
The Arrow system consists of the joint production hypersonic Arrow anti-missile interceptor, Elta EL/M-2080 &quot;Green Pine&quot; early-warning AESA radar,3 the Tadiran Telecom &quot;Golden Citron&quot; (&quot;Citron Tree&quot;) C3I center,4 and the Israel Aerospace Industries &quot;Brown Hazelnut&quot; (&quot;Hazelnut Tree&quot;) launch control center. The system is transportable rather than mobile, as it can be moved to other prepared sites but cannot be set up just anywhere.5
Following construction and testing of the Arrow 1 technology demonstrator,6 production and deployment began with the Arrow 2 version of the missile. The Arrow is considered one of the most advanced missile defense programs currently in existence.78 It is the first operational missile defense system specifically designed and built to intercept and destroy ballistic missiles.910 Arrow 3 is expected in the near future.11 The first Arrow battery was declared fully operational in October 2000.12 Although several of its components have been exported, the Israeli Air Defense Network within the Israeli Air Force (IAF) of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) is currently the sole user of the complete Arrow system.
Background
The Arrow program was launched in light of the acquisition by Arab states of long ranged surface-to-surface missiles.1314 The United States and Israel signed a memorandum of understanding to co-fund it on May 6, 1986,1516 and in 1988 the United States Department of Defense Strategic Defense Initiative Organization (SDIO) placed an order with Israel Aircraft Industries for the Arrow 1 technology demonstrator.1718 The Gulf War, which exposed the controversial performance19 of the Patriot missile against Iraqi &quot;Al Hussein&quot; missiles, gave further impetus to the development of the Arrow.20 It was initially designed to intercept missiles such as &quot;Al Hussein&quot;, its original - SS-1 &quot;Scud&quot;, USSR-made SS-21 &quot;Scarab&quot; of Syria, and China-made CSS-2 of Saudi Arabia.21 Yitzhak Rabin, then Prime Minister of Israel and Defense Minister of Israel, viewed the emerging missile threat as one of the most dangerous future threats on Israel's security.22 He said of the program that:  The Israeli Administration for the Development of Weapons and the Technological Industry, part of the Israeli Ministry of Defense, runs the Arrow development project under the &quot;Homa&quot; missile defense agency which binds together Israel's different defense industries. It is also commonly referred to as the IMDO - Israel Missile Defense Organization.
Funding
The multi-billion dollar development program of the Arrow is undertaken in Israel with the financial support of the United States. When the development program began, the projection for the total cost of its development and manufacture &lt;U+2014&gt; including the initial production of missiles &lt;U+2014&gt; was an estimated $1.6 billion.23 The price of a single Arrow missile was estimated at $3 million.24 Between 1989 and 2007 some $2.4 billion had been reportedly invested in the Arrow program, 50%&lt;U+2013&gt;80%25 of which was funded by the federal government of the United States.26 Israel contributes approximately $65 million annually.27
