Green Pine
Elta, a subsidiary of IAI, was awarded the contract to develop and manufacture the EL/M-2080 &quot;Green Pine&quot; (, ) radar in 1992.178 The &quot;Green Pine&quot; was developed from the Elta &quot;Music&quot; phased array radar,179 presented in November 1994,180 rolled out in 1995,181 and turned operational in November 1998.182 In 2000 it was revealed that the &quot;Green Pine&quot; detected the launch of a Syrian &quot;Scud-D&quot; missile from its base outside Aleppo in northern Syria, and tracked its full trajectory until its impact point, some  in the southern desert.183 The &quot;Green Pine&quot; reportedly detected and tracked similar launches of Syrian &quot;Scuds&quot; also in 2005184 and in 2008.185
The &quot;Green Pine&quot; is an Active Electronically Scanned Array (AESA) solid state radar operating at L band in the range 500 MHz to 1,000 MHz,186 or 1,000 MHz to 2,000 MHz.187 It operates in search, detection, tracking, and missile guidance modes simultaneously.188 It is capable of detecting targets at ranges of up to about  and is able to track targets at speeds over . The radar illuminates the target and guides the Arrow missile to within  of the target.189 The effective radiated power of the &quot;Green Pine&quot; also makes it a possible candidate for conversion into a directed-energy weapon.190
The radar system includes a  wide by  high191 trailer-mounted rotatable antenna array, a power generator, a cooling system and a radar control center.192 The radar comprises 2,000 transmit-receive modules and weighs .193 Its deployment at a new operational site takes &quot;less than 24 hours&quot;.194
An advanced version of the radar, called &quot;Super Green Pine&quot;,195 &quot;Green Pine&quot; Block-B,196 or &quot;Great Pine&quot; (, ), is to take the place of the original &quot;Green Pine. As of 2008 both versions were active.197 The &quot;Super Green Pine&quot; is believed to produce double the power output,198 extending detection range to about .199200201
The Swordfish Long Range Tracking Radar of the Indian Defence Research and Development Organisation is also an acknowledged derivative of the original &quot;Green Pine&quot;.202
Golden Citron
The &quot;Golden Citron&quot; (, ) truck-mounted net-centric open systems architecture203 Battle Management Command, Control, Communication &amp; Intelligence Center204 can control up to 14 intercepts simultaneously.205 As of 2007 it was one of the world's most advanced net-centric systems.206 The system provides fully automatic as well as Human-in-the-Loop options at every stage207 of battle operation management.208 It is also capable of interoperability with other theater missile defense systems and C3I systems.209 Notably Link 16, TADIL-J, communications were being altered to allow interoperability with Patriot fire control units. Assigned targets can be handed over to the Patriot's AN/MPQ-53 fire control radar. Tests carried out by the U.S and Israel have successfully linked the Arrow with both U.S and Israeli versions of the Patriot.210
The &quot;Citron Tree&quot; has three banks of operator consoles laid out in a U shape. In the center sits the officer in command who oversees the engagement, but also has links to the other parts of the battery as well as to IAF headquarters. On the commander's right sits the engagement officer, who ensures that targets are assigned to other engagement officers sitting on the right-hand leg of the U. Each is assigned a geographical area to defend and two of the officers are more senior as they have an overview of Patriot batteries. To the left of the commander is the resource officer, who monitors the status and readiness of the missiles. On the left of the U sits the sky picture officer, who is in contact with the Home Front Command and uses the center's ability to predict impact point to alert the civil authorities. Also at these consoles are an intelligence officer and an after-action / debrief officer, who uses recordings as it is impossible to absorb all the information during engagements.211 All in all, the &quot;Golden Citron&quot; is manned by 7&lt;U+2013&gt;10 operators.212
Brown Hazelnut
The &quot;Brown Hazelnut&quot; (, ) launch control center is located at the launch site,213 up to  from the &quot;Golden Citron&quot; fire control center.214 It employes microwave and radio data and voice communications links to the &quot;Green Pine&quot; and &quot;Golden Citron&quot;. The launch method is a vertical hot launch from a sealed canister,215216 providing all-azimuth coverage.217 &quot;Brown Hazelnut&quot; also has missile maintenance and diagnostic capabilities.218
Production
thumb|upright=1.2|alt=Coverage of Israel provided by two Arrow 2 batteries, derived from their published locations (Palmachim, Ein Shemer) and range (90-100 km). |Coverage of Israel provided by two Arrow 2 batteries, derived from their published locations (Palmachim, Ein Shemer) and range (90-100 km). Israel initially produced the Arrow system domestically,219 but on February 11, 2003 IAI and Boeing signed an agreement, valued at over $25 million for fiscal years 2003&lt;U+2013&gt;2004,220 to establish production facilities for the manufacture of components for the Arrow missile in the United States. In March 2004, IAI awarded a $78 million production contract to Boeing; the total contract value could exceed $225 million through second quarter 2008.221 As a result of successful implementation of this contract Boeing is responsible for production of about 35%222&lt;U+2013&gt;50% of Arrow missile components, including the electronics section, booster motor case and missile canister,223224 at its Huntsville, Alabama facilities.225 IAI, the prime contractor of the Arrow system, is responsible for integration and the final assembly of the Arrow missile in Israel.226 Boeing also coordinates the production of Arrow missile components manufactured by more than 150 American companies.227 Boeing delivered its first Arrow 2 interceptor to Israel in 2005.228229 Co-produced interceptors has been tested since February 12, 2007.230
Other major contractors are:
Elta - produces the &quot;Green Pine&quot; / &quot;Super Green Pine&quot; radar;231
Tadiran Telecom - produces the &quot;Golden Citron&quot; C3I Center;232
Rafael Advanced Defense Systems - produces the sustainer motor and the warhead;233
Israel Military Industries - produces the booster motor;234
Alliant Techsystems - produces the motor cases and the first stage nozzle;235
Lockheed Martin - produces the active radar seeker;236
Raytheon - produces the infrared seeker;237
Ceradyne - produces the ceramic radome.238
Deployment
The first operational Arrow battery was deployed in March 2000 in Palmachim Airbase, near the city of Rishon LeZion, south of the Tel Aviv metropolitan area. It was declared operational in October 2000, and reached its full capacity in March 2001.239 Deployment of the second battery at Ein Shemer,240 near the city of Hadera, Haifa District, northern Israel, was delayed by strong opposition from local residents who feared its radar would be hazardous to their health.241 The situation was eventually resolved and Israel's second battery completed its deployment, turned operational and linked up with first battery in October 2002. In 2007, however, the IDF has reportedly decided to modify its missile defense doctrine and in order to counter possible Syrian and Iranian missile barrages and has modified its deployment of the Arrow in northern Israel.242
Israel had originally planned to deploy two Arrow 2 batteries but has since sought and won promises of funding for a third battery.243 Some reports state that a third battery is already deployed,244 or in development in the south,245 while others claim that a decision on deployment of a third battery has not yet been made, although it is under discussion for service entry in 2012.246 Unconfirmed reports suggest that the first battery is actually in the southern Negev desert, at the Negev Nuclear Research Center near the town of Dimona.247 Another report states that Israel plans to deploy not one, but two additional Arrow 2 batteries to defend the country's southern region, also covering sensitive sites such as the Negev Nuclear Research Center.248 The IDF plans to procure 50249&lt;U+2013&gt;100 interceptors for each battery.250 As of 1998, a battery was estimated to cost about $170 million.251252253
Export
Apart from Israel no country has yet to purchase a full Arrow system, although India had acquired and deployed two &quot;Green Pine&quot; radars around July 2002 and another one in August 2005.254 The Indian government has sought to purchase the Arrow system since 1999,255 however in early 2002 the U.S. vetoed Israel's request to sell the Arrow 2 missiles to India,256257 exercising its right as a major funding contributor.258 U.S. officials argued that the sale would violate the Missile Technology Control Regime (MTCR).259 Although the Arrow 2 could possibly achieve a range of , it is designed for intercepts at shorter ranges, and it is unclear whether it could carry a  payload to this range specified in the MTCR.260261
South Korea was also considering buying two &quot;Green Pine&quot; radars, which would become operational in 2012.262263 Reportedly, South Korea has finally preferred two &quot;Super Green Pine&quot; radars at a cost of $83 million each over its counterpart - ThalesRaytheonSystems' M3R radars.264265 Turkey also planned to buy anti-missile air defense systems worth more than $1 billion. The Arrow was considered a potential contender,266 however Turkey has apparently chosen the Patriot PAC-3.267
In the late 1990s officials of Jordan have expressed concern that any conflagration between Israel and Iraq or Iran would impact its territory. The problem becomes more difficult for Jordan when the warheads are not conventional. Therefore Benjamin Netanyahu, during his first term of office as Prime Minister of Israel, reportedly offered Jordan &quot;a defensive umbrella of Arrow 2&quot;. Without allowing Israel to forward deploy the Arrow launchers close to the Iraqi border, the other option is for Israel to sell Jordan the Arrow system. This is most likely what Prime Minister Netanyahu meant above. In May 1999 Israel reportedly requested U.S. approval for selling Arrow batteries to Jordan, but apparently no such approval has been given yet.268
In the past, the United Kingdom, Japan, and Singapore were mentioned as then potential foreign customers of the Arrow system.269270 Netherlands reportedly expressed interest in the &quot;Golden Citron&quot; C3I center in November 1999.271
For the United States, the Arrow has provided important technical and operational data.272 It remains a key element in the Missile Defense Agency&lt;U+2019&gt;s plan for a layered missile defense architecture, and an example of a successful, affordable program. At the moment, however, the United States does not have any plans to procure and deploy the Arrow.273 Nevertheless in September 2009 the Arrow system was mentioned by U.S. Secretary of Defense Robert Gates and Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff General James Cartwright among the alternative to the proposed U.S. missile defense assets in Europe.274275 Currently the Arrow system is being incorporated into U.S. anti-ballistic capability in Europe, they said.276
